{
"issue_number": 1,
"question": "Whether the plaintiff alleged a concrete and particularized injury in fact sufficient to establish Article III standing based on the disclosure of anonymized medical records.",
"holding": "No; the plaintiff failed to allege a concrete, actual, or imminent injury arising from the disclosure of anonymized records.",
"ratio": "Article III standing requires a concrete and particularized injury that is real, not abstract, and plausibly alleged; the transfer of anonymized data without identification or demonstrable harm does not constitute a concrete injury."
},
{
"issue_number": 2,
"question": "Whether an alleged invasion of privacy based on the transfer of anonymized medical records constitutes a concrete injury in fact.",
"holding": "No; without identifiability or actual disclosure of identifiable private information, the alleged privacy invasion is too speculative to constitute a concrete injury.",
"ratio": "A privacy-based injury must have a close relationship to traditionally recognized common-law harms and must involve identifiable disclosure; dissemination of anonymized information without identifiability does not establish a concrete injury."
},
{
"issue_number": 3,
"question": "Whether the risk of future reidentification from anonymized medical records is sufficient to establish standing for damages or injunctive relief.",
"holding": "No; the alleged risk of future reidentification is speculative and not certainly impending, and thus insufficient to support standing.",
"ratio": "A risk of future harm supports standing only if it is imminent and substantial for prospective relief, and cannot support damages unless the harm has materialized."
},
{
"issue_number": 4,
"question": "Whether alleged pecuniary harms based on overpayment for medical services or underpayment for the use of medical information establish injury in fact.",
"holding": "No; the asserted pecuniary injuries were implausible and unsupported by factual allegations demonstrating actual loss.",
"ratio": "Pecuniary injury must be plausibly alleged and grounded in actual loss to the plaintiff; speculative overpayment theories or claims based solely on a defendant’s gain do not establish injury in fact."
},
{
"issue_number": 5,
"question": "Whether an alleged breach of contract, without accompanying concrete harm, is sufficient to establish Article III standing.",
"holding": "No; a bare breach of contract without a resulting concrete injury is an injury in law, not an injury in fact.",
"ratio": "Article III requires a concrete factual harm distinct from a legal violation; a breach of contract alone, without real-world injury, does not satisfy the injury-in-fact requirement."
}
],
"court_decision": {
"holding": "The plaintiff lacked Article III standing because he failed to allege a concrete, particularized, and actual or imminent injury.",
"outcome": "Judgment affirmed as modified to reflect dismissal for lack of jurisdiction based on lack of standing.",
"reasoning": [
"1. Article III requires a plaintiff to demonstrate an injury in fact that is concrete, particularized, and actual or imminent, traceable to the defendant, and redressable by the court.",
"2. The disclosure of anonymized medical records did not constitute a concrete privacy injury because the plaintiff did not plausibly allege that he was identifiable from the data.",
"3. The alleged risk that Google might reidentify the plaintiff in the future was speculative and not certainly impending, and therefore insufficient to support standing for damages or injunctive relief.",
"4. The plaintiff’s theories of pecuniary harm—overpayment for medical services and entitlement to profits from use of data—were implausible and unsupported by factual allegations of actual loss.",
"5. A defendant’s gain alone cannot establish injury in fact; standing requires a loss to the plaintiff.",
"6. A breach of contract without accompanying real-world harm is only an injury in law and does not meet Article III’s requirement of a concrete injury in fact.",
"7. Because none of the alleged privacy, financial, or contractual injuries satisfied the injury-in-fact requirement, the plaintiff lacked standing to pursue any claims.",
"8. Without standing, federal courts lack jurisdiction, requiring dismissal of the case."
