"issue_number": 1,
"question": "Whether the employee is likely to prevail on the merits of his workers’ compensation claim where he did not provide timely written notice of a work-related injury within the statutory period.",
"holding": "No; the employee is unlikely to prevail because he did not provide timely written notice and did not establish actual knowledge or a reasonable excuse.",
"ratio": "An employee must provide written notice of a work-related injury within the statutory time period unless the employer had actual knowledge of the injury or the employee shows a reasonable excuse for delay; failure to satisfy all three elements requires denial of the claim."
},
{
"issue_number": 2,
"question": "Whether the employer had actual knowledge of the employee’s alleged work-related injury sufficient to excuse the absence of timely written notice.",
"holding": "No; the employer did not have actual knowledge of a work-related injury.",
"ratio": "Actual knowledge requires credible proof that the employer was made aware of a work-related injury; absent reliable evidence or documentation, the requirement is not satisfied."
},
{
"issue_number": 3,
"question": "Whether the employee demonstrated a reasonable excuse for failing to provide timely written notice of a work-related injury.",
"holding": "No; the employee did not present or argue a reasonable excuse for failing to provide timely written notice.",
"ratio": "If an employee neither provides timely written notice nor proves actual knowledge by the employer, the claim must be denied unless a reasonable excuse for the failure is established."
}
],
"court_decision": {
"holding": "The employee failed to establish that he provided timely written notice, that the employer had actual knowledge, or that he had a reasonable excuse, making him unlikely to prevail on the merits.",
"outcome": "Request for medical and temporary disability benefits denied; status conference scheduled.",
"reasoning": [
"1. At an expedited hearing, the employee bears the burden of proving he is likely to prevail at a hearing on the merits.",
"2. Tennessee law requires an employee to provide written notice of a work-related injury within 15 days unless the employer had actual knowledge or the employee shows a reasonable excuse.",
"3. The court applied the multi-step framework for notice: whether timely written notice was given, whether the employer had actual knowledge, and whether a reasonable excuse exists.",
"4. The court found the employee did not provide timely written notice because the first documented report was an initial incident form signed on June 23, 2023.",
"5. The court found the employee’s testimony about providing earlier written and verbal notice on April 27 was not credible and contained inconsistencies.",
"6. Employer records showed no documentation that human resources personnel were notified in April 2023.",
"7. The court determined the employer did not have actual knowledge because the employee initially sought treatment for chronic back pain and did not identify it as a work-related injury.",
"8. The employee did not argue or establish a reasonable excuse for failing to give timely notice.",
"9. Because the employee failed all prongs of the notice analysis, he was unlikely to prevail on the merits and benefits were denied."
]
