"issue_number": 1,
"question": "Whether the district court constructively denied Amazon’s motion for a temporary restraining order and preliminary injunction by failing to rule before September 27, thereby creating appellate jurisdiction under 28 U.S.C. § 1292(a)(1).",
"holding": "No; the district court did not constructively deny the motion, and therefore no interlocutory appellate jurisdiction existed.",
"ratio": "A district court’s failure to rule on a preliminary injunction motion constitutes an effective denial only when the movant demonstrates both diligence in seeking expedited consideration and a legitimate basis for urgency; delay alone, without these showings, does not create an appealable interlocutory order."
}
],
"court_decision": {
"holding": "The court lacked subject-matter jurisdiction because the district court did not effectively deny Amazon’s motion for injunctive relief.",
"outcome": "Appeal dismissed.",
"reasoning": [
"1. Appellate jurisdiction under 28 U.S.C. § 1292(a)(1) extends to interlocutory orders that expressly or effectively refuse injunctive relief.",
"2. An effective denial may occur when a district court’s delay in ruling renders preliminary relief useless, but this determination is contextual.",
"3. The court considers whether the movant acted diligently in seeking expedited review and whether a legitimate basis for urgency exists.",
"4. Amazon did not diligently pursue expedited relief because it failed to repeatedly request a ruling by a specific date and did not seek an expedited briefing schedule or hearing.",
"5. Amazon made a specific request for a ruling only once, approximately one day before the deadline it claimed was critical.",
"6. Amazon did not establish a legitimate basis for urgency because the possibility of an immediate NLRB decision was speculative and Amazon acknowledged such decisions typically take weeks or months.",
"7. The district court acted promptly by holding a hearing and issuing a decision one business day after supplemental briefing was completed.",
"8. A litigant cannot create appellate jurisdiction merely by asserting that the district court failed to rule within a preferred timeline.",
"9. Because there was no effective denial of injunctive relief, there was no appealable interlocutory order, and the appeal had to be dismissed for lack of subject-matter jurisdiction."
]
