"issues_analysis": [
{
"issue_number": 1,
"question": "Whether a pre-suit discovery complaint under R.C. 2317.48 that seeks information to determine if a cause of action exists states a valid claim for discovery.",
"holding": "No, a pre-suit discovery complaint that seeks information to determine whether a cause of action exists does not state a valid claim under R.C. 2317.48.",
"ratio": "An action for pre-suit discovery under R.C. 2317.48 is permitted only to uncover specific facts necessary to plead an already identified claim, not to conduct a fishing expedition to determine whether a cause of action exists."
},
{
"issue_number": 2,
"question": "Whether the plaintiff’s complaint alleged sufficient facts to state a plausible claim for relief, including breach of contract, under Civ.R. 12(B)(6).",
"holding": "No, the complaint failed to allege the existence of a contract or necessary elements of breach and therefore did not state a claim upon which relief could be granted.",
"ratio": "To survive a Civ.R. 12(B)(6) motion, a complaint must allege facts supporting each element of a cognizable legal claim, including the existence of a contract, performance, breach, and damages in a breach-of-contract action."
}
],
"court_decision": {
"holding": "The trial court properly granted Amazon’s Civ.R. 12(B)(6) motion to dismiss because the complaint failed to state a claim upon which relief could be granted.",
"outcome": "Judgment affirmed.",
"reasoning": [
"1. A Civ.R. 12(B)(6) motion tests the legal sufficiency of the complaint, and courts must accept the material allegations as true while determining whether any set of facts could entitle the plaintiff to relief.",
"2. The complaint, titled a pre-suit discovery action, sought information about book sales to determine whether a cause of action existed rather than to clarify facts necessary to plead a specific claim.",
"3. R.C. 2317.48 permits pre-suit discovery only when necessary to plead a known claim and does not allow broad discovery to explore whether a claim might exist.",
"4. The plaintiff’s request for information about the number of books sold constituted an impermissible fishing expedition rather than a targeted request to support a defined cause of action.",
"5. Because the complaint failed to identify a justiciable underlying claim requiring discovery, it did not state a valid action under R.C. 2317.48.",
"6. Even if construed as a substantive lawsuit, the complaint failed to allege facts supporting a breach-of-contract claim, including the existence of a contract, performance, breach, or resulting damages.",
"7. The complaint also did not identify a recognized legal cause of action to enforce compliance with a prior subpoena or cite any supporting authority.",
"8. Accordingly, the pleading failed to state a claim upon which relief could be granted, and dismissal under Civ.R. 12(B)(6) was proper."
]
},
