"question": "Whether the statute of limitations barred the employee’s left-shoulder claim when the petition for benefit determination listed only a right-shoulder injury.",
"holding": "The statute of limitations did not bar the left-shoulder claim because the petition was filed within one year of the last payment and no rule required contemporaneous pleading of all injuries.",
"ratio": "When an employer has paid benefits, a workers’ compensation claim is timely if filed within the statutory period following the last payment, and failure to list additional injuries in the original petition does not automatically bar later-asserted related conditions absent a rule requiring specific contemporaneous pleading."
},
{
"issue_number": 2,
"question": "Whether the employee demonstrated that her left-shoulder condition was work-related and likely compensable so as to justify medical and temporary disability benefits at an expedited hearing.",
"holding": "The employee failed to show she was likely to prove compensability because no medical evidence connected the left-shoulder condition to her employment or to the compensable right-shoulder injury.",
"ratio": "In workers’ compensation proceedings, an employee bears the burden of proving, through competent medical evidence and to a reasonable degree of medical certainty, that an injury arose primarily out of employment or as a direct and natural consequence of a compensable injury; courts cannot infer causation without expert proof."
}
],
"court_decision": {
"holding": "The employee’s claim was timely but she failed to establish that her left-shoulder injury was work-related, so her request for medical treatment and temporary disability benefits was denied.",
"outcome": "Relief denied; case set for status hearing with opportunity to present additional medical proof.",
"reasoning": [
"1. The statute of limitations defense failed because the last workers’ compensation payment occurred on June 4, 2020, and the petition was filed on May 13, 2021, within one year.",
"2. The employer cited no authority requiring a claimant to list all injured body parts in the initial petition for purposes of the statute of limitations.",
"3. To obtain additional treatment, the employee had to show that her left-shoulder condition arose primarily out of and in the course and scope of employment or was a direct and natural consequence of the compensable right-shoulder injury.",
"4. Medical proof must establish, to a reasonable degree of medical certainty, that employment contributed more than fifty percent to the injury.",
"5. The medical records reflected complaints of left-shoulder pain and diagnostic findings but contained no medical opinion linking the condition to employment or to overuse caused by the right-shoulder injury.",
"6. Although the court found the employee’s testimony about overuse credible and plausible, credibility alone cannot substitute for expert medical causation evidence.",
"7. Because the employee did not establish a likely causal connection, she did not meet her burden of proof at the expedited stage.",
"8. Without a compensable left-shoulder injury, the employee also could not establish eligibility for temporary disability benefits, which require proof of disability resulting from a compensable injury."
]
